<StaticPage
  title="Write for ChevyRoots"
  description="ChevyRoots is looking for Chevy enthusiasts who can write honestly and well. Pitch a story, a build, or a guide."
  eyebrow="Contributors"
  heading="Write for Us"
>
  <p>ChevyRoots is always looking for enthusiasts who can write honestly and well about Chevys. If you own one, wrench on one, restore one, race one, or just love them — and you can string sentences together — we want to hear from you.</p>

  <h2>What we're looking for</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Build stories</strong> — your own build, or a friend's, with photos and honest detail</li>
    <li><strong>Ownership experiences</strong> — "6 months with a [whatever]", "what I wish I knew before buying," "the mod that was actually worth it"</li>
    <li><strong>Event reports</strong> — if you're going to a car show or cruise in your region, let us cover it</li>
    <li><strong>Regional knowledge</strong> — "best Chevy dealer in [your city]", "where to take a classic Chevy in [your region]"</li>
    <li><strong>Mechanical deep-dives</strong> — if you've dealt with a specific issue (AFM lifters, 10-speed shudder, electrical gremlins) and have a real fix story, we want it</li>
    <li><strong>History pieces</strong> — any model, any era, any angle, as long as you know your stuff</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What we're NOT looking for</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>SEO-farm rewrites of other people's articles</li>
    <li>Press-release regurgitation</li>
    <li>"Top 10 [whatever]" slideshows</li>
    <li>AI-generated content (we can tell, and so can readers)</li>
    <li>Anything negative about a dealership written as an axe-grinding vendetta</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to pitch</h2>
  <p>Email <a href="mailto:hello@chevyroots.com?subject=Writer%20Pitch">hello@chevyroots.com</a> with "Writer Pitch" in the subject line. In the email:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A 2–3 sentence pitch of the story you want to write</li>
    <li>A link or PDF to something you've written before (personal blog, forum thread, Reddit post, LinkedIn article — anything showing you can write)</li>
    <li>Your background with Chevys (owner, mechanic, restorer, enthusiast, historian, whatever)</li>
    <li>Whether the piece already exists or you need to write it</li>
  </ul>

  <p>We respond to every pitch, usually within a week.</p>

  <h2>Compensation</h2>
  <p>We pay for commissioned pieces. Rates depend on length, research depth, and whether you're providing original photos. Contact us for specifics.</p>

  <p>We also accept submissions from hobbyist writers who don't want payment — those get full byline credit, author bio, social link, and if you want, a free ChevyRoots enamel pin when we launch merch.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Accuracy first.</strong> Verify your claims. We fact-check before publishing.</li>
    <li><strong>Honesty over promotion.</strong> If it's bad, say so. If it's good, explain why.</li>
    <li><strong>Original photos preferred.</strong> Stock photos are a last resort.</li>
    <li><strong>Your voice matters.</strong> We don't flatten bylines into a house style. If you're funny, be funny. If you're technical, be technical.</li>
    <li><strong>Disclose everything.</strong> If you work at a dealership, tell us. If a shop comped your work, tell us.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Questions? <a href="/contact/">Contact us</a>.</p>
</StaticPage>
